def domain_features(df,features):
    for feature in features:
        print("Number of different value for '",feature,"': " , len(df[feature].unique()))

Data Exploration¶

“Torture the data, and it will confess to anything.”

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is the process of visualizing and analyzing data to extract insights from it. In other words, EDA is the process of summarizing important characteristics of data in order to gain better understanding of the dataset.

Load the dataset¶

we are collecting the datas into a pandas Dataframe that gives you the possibility to work with great flexibility and enjoying the huge amount of methods that pandas provides for manipulate and analyze the datasets

Let's get an idea of our dataset: What we can predict here is about the course of dimensionality,that can be defined by the situation where basically with an enormous number of features and not enough representative samples, model performance starts getting affected often leading to overfitting. The rule of thumb in this situation is to own a number of istances that is, at least, one order of magnitude greater than the number of features, that here are labelled as "Columns"

At first look, it is possible to retrieve some usefull information about out dataset:

  1. Excluding the ID, there are almost two kind of features related to our dataset:
    • the first one are categorical and encoded (in the first table we can see the coded categories, where one real number represent one particular categorical value). As we will see, the numbers selected for representing the categories are not randoms. In the second table there the "explained" categories (all but some psicological scores that are meaningless for human beings)
    • the other ones are the "Addiction" classes and are coded in 7 element (from 0 to 6), representing, as we will see, a grade of addiction to the named substance that goes from Not User (0) at "User in the last days" (6). Its look perfect as labels for Multiclass Classification problem.

Dataset General Information¶

From the official UCI Dataset Repository, we have a deep description of our dataset

Abstract: Classify type of drug consumer by personality data
Data Set Characteristics: Multivariate
Number of Instances: 1885
Attribute Characteristics: Real
Number of Attributes:32
Associated Tasks:Classification
Missing Values? N/A
Number of Web Hits: 77254

Data Set Information:¶

Database contains records for 1885 respondents. For each respondent 12 attributes are known: Personality measurements which include NEO-FFI-R (neuroticism, extraversion, openness to experience, agreeableness, and conscientiousness), BIS-11 (impulsivity), and ImpSS (sensation seeking), level of education, age, gender, country of residence and ethnicity. All input attributes are originally categorical and are quantified. After quantification values of all input features can be considered as real-valued. In addition, participants were questioned concerning their use of 18 legal and illegal drugs (alcohol, amphetamines, amyl nitrite, benzodiazepine, cannabis, chocolate, cocaine, caffeine, crack, ecstasy, heroin, ketamine, legal highs, LSD, methadone, mushrooms, nicotine and volatile substance abuse and one fictitious drug (Semeron) which was introduced to identify over-claimers. For each drug they have to select one of the answers: never used the drug, used it over a decade ago, or in the last decade, year, month, week, or day. Database contains 18 classification problems. Each of independent label variables contains seven classes: "Never Used", "Used over a Decade Ago", "Used in Last Decade", "Used in Last Year", "Used in Last Month", "Used in Last Week", and "Used in Last Day".

Problem which can be solved¶

  • Seven class classifications for each drug separately.
  • Problem can be transformed to binary classification by union of part of classes into one new class. For example, "Never Used", "Used over a Decade Ago" form class "Non-user" and all other classes form class "User".
  • The best binarization of classes for each attribute.
  • Evaluation of risk to be drug consumer for each drug.

1.5 Heatmap Correlation Plot¶

Here we can see the Heatmap Correlation Plot, means an heatmap that represent the value of correlation measured for each couple of feature of our dataset. Obviously, the upper-right part is equally to the lower-left one, splitted by the "1" diagonal that is the correlation of each feature with itself.

Correlation is a statistical term which in common usage refers to how close two variables are to having a linear relationship with each other. For example, two variables which are linearly dependent (say, x and y which depend on each other as x = 2y) will have a higher correlation than two variables which are non-linearly dependent (say, u and v which depend on each other as u = v2).

Specifically, Pearson Correlation is defined as:

$$ \text{Cor}(X,Y) = \frac{{}\sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - \overline{x})(y_i - \overline{y})} {{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - \overline{x})^2}}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \overline{y})^2}}} $$

The values of the correlation coefficient can range from -1 to +1. The closer it is to +1 or -1, the more closely are the two variables are related. The positive sign signifies the direction of the correlation i.e. if one of the variables increases, the other variable is also supposed to increase, otherwise if the sign is negative, the trend is opposite.

Features with high correlation are more linearly dependent and hence have almost the same effect on the dependent variable. So, when two features have high correlation, eventually we can drop one of the two features. Meanwhile, looking at the class choosen for classification, the correlated features will be the ones more usefull for our estimator, so it is a way to display the importance of a determinated predictor knowing the prediction goal.

In [44]:
# Compute the correlation matrix
corr = data.corr()
# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 20))

            square=True, linewidths=0, cbar_kws={"shrink": .8})

This correlogram give us the possibility to deeply understand correlation between variables: it is so important to understand if two variable are strongly correlated, becouse their contribute to classification is strongly bounded, and we can keep just one of two of these without loosing too accuracy for the model. Looking at the graph, the attention goes quickly to the right-low area of the correlation matrix, that is most red-painted that the rest of the square: this area is formed by the correlation of "hard drugs" features, so our simple interpretation is that the consumption of these drugs goes parallely and when your are, for example, an Ecstasy Consumer, the risk to fall in addiction with other drugs (particularly LSD, or Mushrooms) is greater. As reported in other scientific articles, Correlation analysis demonstrated the existence of groups of drugs with strongly correlated consumption patterns. Three correlation pleiades were identified, named by the central drug in the pleiade: ecstasy, heroin, and benzodiazepines pleiades.

Clustermap¶

Finally let's see the Cluster map, that sostantially plot a matrix dataset as a hierarchically-clustered heatmap. Clustering refers to a very broad set of techinques for finding subgroups, or cluster, in a dataset. The clusters are made by defining groups of nearest elements: so it is necessary to define a similarity measure () Hierarchichal clustering is an alternative to prototyope-based clustering algorithms. The main advantage of Hierarchichal clustering is that we do not need to specify the number of clusters, it will find it by itself. In addition, it enables the plotting of dendograms. Dendograms are visualizations of a binary hierarchichal clustering.

Let's move our attention to the upper dendogram. Becouse of the measure choosen (correlation) graph is so related to the correlation matrix seen before: as the one above, here we can see relation between features and how its will be used in a hierarchical clustering. So it is natural that the first relations between two features are ever with the most correlated one; that's becouse the metric choosen, that is correlation (but, honestly, it doesn't change for euclidean distance measure).

ML Beginning Analysis¶

Dataset provides 19 different classes to be goal of prediction: Alcohol, Amphet, Amyl, Benzos, Caff, Cannabis, Choc, Coke, Crack, Ecstasy, Heroin, Ketamine, Legalh, LSD, Meth, Mushrooms, Nicotine, Semer, VSA.

Possible approaches for classification are:

  • Seven class classifications for each drug separately.
  • Problem can be transformed to binary classification by union of part of classes into one new class. For example, "Never Used", "Used over a Decade Ago" form class "Non-user" and all other classes form class "User".
  • The best binarization of classes for each attribute.
  • Evaluation of risk to be drug consumer for each drug.

Classification Problem Definition¶

So, we have to define our classification problem, by choosing a class to be object of our prediction, and in which form it will be given, depending on the classification algorithm it will provides.

Thus, I select the LSD consumption as the feature used for classification problem.

We will provides 2 kind of work for make the prediction:

  • trying to predict multiclass classification (7, from 0 to 6).
  • trying to predict two class classification by using a binary trasformation of the feature as shown before ("Never Used", "Used over a Decade Ago" and "Used in last Decade" form class "Non-user" and all other classes form class "User".)

Data Manipulation for ML Analysis¶

we will now extract our "LSD" as the output array (y), than generate the equivalent for binary classification problem, and making the training and test set definition.

Then we focus on the feature univariate distribution and we discover that features are already coded into normal sequence of values.
